SIMPLE: spare
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spare
<hw>Spare</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Spared</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sparing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>sparian</ets>, fr.
<ets>spaer</ets> spare, sparing, saving; akin to D. & G.
<ets>sparen</ets>, OHG. <ets>spar<?/n</ets>, Icel. & Sw.
<ets>spara</ets>, Dan. <ets>spare</ets> See <er>Spare</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To use frugally or stintingly, as
that which is scarce or valuable; to retain or keep unused; to
save.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧No cost would he <xex>spare</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Thou] thy Father's dreadful thunder didst not
<qex>spare</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that hath knowledge, <qex>spareth</qex> his words.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. xvii. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To keep to one's self; to forbear to impart or
give.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be pleased your plitics to <qex>spare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Spare</qex> my sight the pain⟦br⟧
Of seeing what a world of tears it costs you.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To preserve from danger or punishment; to forbear to
punish, injure, or harm; to show mercy to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Spare</qex> us, good Lord.</q> <rj><qau>Book of Common
Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dim sadness did not <qex>spare</qex>⟦br⟧
That time celestial visages.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man alone can whom he conquers <qex>spare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To save or gain, as by frugality; to reserve, as
from some occupation, use, or duty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the time he could <qex>spare</qex> from the necessary cares of
his weighty charge, he bestowed on . . . serving of God.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To deprive one's self of, as by being frugal; to do
without; to dispense with; to give up; to part with.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where angry Jove did never <qex>spare</qex>⟦br⟧
One breath of kind and temperate air.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could have better <qex>spared</qex> a better man.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To spare one's self</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To act
with reserve.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her thought that a lady should <qex>her spare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To save one's self labor, punishment, or
blame.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Spare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spare
<hw>Spare</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be
frugal; not to be profuse; to live frugally; to be
parsimonious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I, who at some times spend, at others <qex>spare</qex>,⟦br⟧
Divided between carelessness and care.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To refrain from inflicting harm; to use mercy or
forbearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will not <qex>spare</qex> in the day of vengeance.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. vi. 34.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To desist; to stop; to refrain.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spare
<hw>Spare</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sparer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sparest</adjf>; -- not used in all the senses of the
word.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>spaer</ets> sparing. Cf. <er>Spare</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Scanty; not abundant or
plentiful; <as>as, a <ex>spare</ex> diet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sparing; frugal; parsimonious; chary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was <qex>spare</qex>, but discreet of speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Carew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Being over and above what is necessary, or what must
be used or reserved; not wanted, or not used; superfluous; <as>as, I
have no <ex>spare</ex> time</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If that no <qex>spare</qex> clothes he had to give.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Held in reserve, to be used in an emergency; <as>as,
a <ex>spare</ex> anchor; a <ex>spare</ex> bed or room.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Lean; wanting flesh; meager; thin; gaunt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, give me the <qex>spare</qex> men, and spare me the great
ones.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Slow.</def> <mark>[Obs. or prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Grose.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spare</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spare
<hw>Spare</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
sparing; moderation; restraint.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Killing for sacrifice, without any <qex>spare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Parsimony; frugal use.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Poured out their plenty without spite or <qex>spare</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An opening in a petticoat or gown; a placket.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which has not been used or expended.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Tenpins)</fld> <def>The right of bowling again at a
full set of pins, after having knocked all the pins down in less than
three bowls. If all the pins are knocked down in one bowl it is a
<xex>double spare</xex>; in two bowls, a <xex>single spare</xex>. For
the meaning in modern bowling, see sense 6.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Bowling)</fld> <def>The act of knocking down all
ten pins in two bowls, which entitles the bowler to add the number of
pins knocked down in the next bowl to the score for the frame in which
the spare occurred.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spareful</ent>⟦br⟧
